{{Infobox NFL biography |name=Don Carothers |image= |number=86 |position=[[Offensive end]] |birth_date={{birth date|1934|5|13}} |birth_place=[[Moline, Illinois]] |death_date={{death date and age|2008|9|18|1934|5|13}} |death_place=[[Wilson, North Carolina]] |height_ft=6 |height_in=5 |weight_lbs=225 |high_school=[[Moline High School|Moline (IL)]] |college=[[Bradley Braves football|Bradley]] |draftyear=1957 |draftround=10 |draftpick=118 |pastteams= * [[Chicago Cardinals (NFL, 1920–59)|Chicago Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|1958}})* * [[Denver Broncos]] ([[1960 American Football League season|1960]]) |pastteamsnote=yes |nflnew=doncarothers/2511101 |pfr=C/CaroDo00 }} '''Donald E. "Crutch" Carothers''' (May 13, 1934 – September 19, 2008) was an [[American football]] [[offensive end]] who played one season with the [[Denver Broncos]] of the [[American Football League]] (AFL). He was drafted by the [[Chicago Cardinals (NFL, 1920–59)|Chicago Cardinals]] in the tenth round of the [[1957 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Bradley University]] and attended [[Moline High School]] in [[Moline, Illinois]].<ref name="A">{{cite web | url=http://www.profootballarchives.com/caro01000.html | title=DON CAROTHERS | publisher=profootballarchives.com | accessdate=October 24, 2015}}</ref>
==Early years== Carothers participated in [[high school football]], basketball and [[Track and field|track]] for the Moline High School Maroons. He was a member of the 1951 Maroons basketball team that finished second in the state.<ref name="B">{{cite web |url=http://www.qconline.com/news/local/remembering-don-carothers/article_e2ffb300-9820-5372-b16b-6cacf86381f1.html |title=Remembering Don Carothers |publisher=qconline.com |date=September 22, 2008 |accessdate=October 24, 2015 |author=Marx, John |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cWe35QaV?url=http://www.qconline.com/news/local/remembering-don-carothers/article_e2ffb300-9820-5372-b16b-6cacf86381f1.html |archivedate=October 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref> He also won the Illinois state high jump title for three consecutive years.<ref name="C">{{cite web|url=http://www.deroofuneralhome.com/memsol.cgi?user_id=41608 |title=DONALD E. CAROTHERS |publisher=deroofuneralhome.com |accessdate=October 24, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024200455/http://www.deroofuneralhome.com/memsol.cgi?user_id=41608 |archivedate=October 24, 2015 }}</ref>
==College career== Carothers first attended the [[University of Iowa]] on a basketball scholarship.<ref name="C"/> He transferred to [[Bradley University]] and was a [[Letterman (sports)|letterman]] in football, basketball and track for the Braves. He was a member of the Braves basketball team that won the [[1957 National Invitation Tournament|1957 NIT championship]]. Carothers was also the team's leading receiver and punter in football his senior season. He was later inducted into the Bradley University Athletic Hall of Fame.<ref name="B"/>
==Professional career== Carothers was selected by the [[Chicago Cardinals (NFL, 1920–59)|Chicago Cardinals]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) with the 118th pick in the [[1957 NFL Draft]].<ref name="A"/> He signed with the Cardinals on June 3, 1958, after his senior year at Bradley.<ref name="B"/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19580604&id=OH9QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cBAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3192,1700258&hl=en | title=Signs Grid Pact | work=[[The Milwaukee Sentinel]] | date=June 4, 1958 | agency=[[United Press International]] | accessdate=October 24, 2015}}</ref> He was released by the Cardinals on September 15, 1958.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/22373143/ |title=The Chicago Cardinals cut their squad to 38 by asking waivers |work=Daily Inter Lake |date=September 16, 1958 |accessdate=October 24, 2015 |pages=5 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151024202125/http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/22373143/ |archivedate=October 24, 2015 }}</ref> Carothers signed with the AFL's [[Denver Broncos]] in 1960 and played in three games for the team during the [[1960 American Football League season|1960 season]].<ref name="A"/><ref name="B"/>
==Personal life== Carothers worked as an insurance agent and also in the investment field after his football career.<ref name="B"/><ref name="C"/> He was later the owner of the Carothers Insurance Company in [[Bettendorf, Iowa]].<ref name="C"/> He also was the general manager of the Quad City Raiders, which played in the [[Continental Football League]].<ref name="B"/>
