{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}

The '''St. Petersburg Human Rights Ordinance''' is a law that was passed in January 2002 in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]. This law added sexual orientation as a protected status in housing, employment, and public accommodations. This movement was lead by Equality Florida's leader Nadine Smith, which took years to pass due to overruling in city meetings. [[Equality Florida]] is an advocacy group that advocates for equal LGBTQ rights for all Florida residents. This organization played a heavy hand in passing the first St. Petersburg Human rights ordinance .<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eqfl.org/Discrimination|title=Discrimination {{!}} Equality Florida|website=www.eqfl.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stpete.org/vision/points_of_pride.php|title=Mayor's Points of Pride - St. Petersburg|last=|first=|date=|website=www.stpete.org|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-04}}</ref>

For the years leading up to this event, the offices of St. Petersburg were consistently receiving mail from communities in an effort to address the city's failure to protect the LGBTQ community from discrimination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com|title=City to address human rights ordinance|last=Lapeter|first=Leonora|date=2001-11-02|work=The St. Petersburg Times|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref> The bill to pass sexual orientation as an addition to the human rights ordinance was previously denied in a county commissioners meeting in 2001. This means that discrimination against age, race, and gender was still prohibited in the workplace, real estate and in public, but sexual orientation is excluded from this law<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com|title=Human rights ordinance omits sexual orientation|last=Humphrey|first=Joe|date=2000-10-06|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref>. While supporters argued that this ordinance offers further protection in addition to civil rights laws, opposers of this ordinance argued that the city shouldn't have to further protect those with "alternate lifestyles".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/|title=Commission to vote on human rights ordinance|last=Tan|first=Shannon|date=2003-08-05|work=The St. Petersburg Times|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref> It wasn't until January of 2002 that the human right ordinance law was passed which protected discrimination against rage, gender, age AND sexual orientation in St. Petersburg. This later lead to the passing of Pinellas county's own human rights ordinance that protected against the same discriminations in 2008. <ref name=":0" />

